what is server access login in s3?

Server Access Logging means S3 records detailed logs of every request made to your bucket — who accessed it, what they did, when, and from where.

Every time someone accesses your bucket, S3 records:

Who made the request?      → IP address, requester identity
What did they do?          → GET, PUT, DELETE etc.
Which object?              → object name/key
When?                      → date and time
Was it successful?         → HTTP status code (200, 403, 404)
How much data transferred? → bytes sent
How long did it take?      → response time


Two Buckets Needed

Source Bucket          Log Bucket
(your actual data)  →  (where logs are saved)

mybucket            →  mybucket-logs

How to Enable Server Access Logging

Step 1 — Create a Log Bucket

Create a separate S3 bucket to store logs
e.g. my-bucket-access-logs
Must be in the same region as source bucket

Step 2 — Enable Logging on Source Bucket

S3 Console → Your Source Bucket
Click Properties tab
Scroll to Server access logging
Click Edit
Select Enable
Choose your log bucket
Set a prefix (optional) e.g. logs/
Click Save

what is object lock in s3?

S3 Object Lock means you can prevent objects from being deleted or overwritten for a fixed period or indefinitely — even by the root user or administrators.

Without Object Lock:
  Anyone with permissions can delete or overwrite your file ❌

With Object Lock:
  File is LOCKED — nobody can delete or modify it
  until the lock expires ✅

Important Requirements
⚠️ Object Lock must be enabled at bucket creation time

You cannot enable it on an existing bucket
Once enabled, versioning is automatically enabled and cannot be disabled

How to Enable Object Lock
Step 1 — Enable at Bucket Creation

S3 Console → Create Bucket
Scroll to Object Lock
Check Enable Object Lock
Click Create Bucket

