What is ACL in s3?

ACL is a legacy access control mechanism that defines who can access your S3 buckets and objects, and what actions they can perform.

Think of ACL like a Guest List at a party:

Without ACL:
  Only you (owner) can enter ✅

With ACL:
  You add specific people/groups
  and define what they can do
  (read, write, full control) ✅

Two Types of ACL

ACL
 ├── Bucket ACL   → controls access to the bucket itself
 └── Object ACL   → controls access to individual objects

| Permission       | Bucket Level           | Object Level     |
| ---------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------- |
| **READ**         | List objects in bucket | Read object data |
| **WRITE**        | Add/delete objects     | Not applicable   |
| **READ_ACP**     | Read bucket ACL        | Read object ACL  |
| **WRITE_ACP**    | Write bucket ACL       | Write object ACL |
| **FULL_CONTROL** | All permissions        | All permissions  |


What is bucket policy?

⚠️ ACL is disabled by default since April 2023 — must enable manually. AWS recommends Bucket Policy instead.

Bucket Policy controls access at the entire bucket level using JSON rules. More powerful and flexible than ACL.



{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "statement name",
      "Effect": "Allow or Deny",
      "Principal": "who",
      "Action": "what action",
      "Resource": "which bucket/object",
      "Condition": "when (optional)"
    }
  ]
}


1 — Make Entire Bucket Public (Read Only)

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicRead",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::YOUR-BUCKET-NAME/*"
    }
  ]
}


🔹 ACL vs Bucket Policy – Key Differences

| Feature              | ACL                  | Bucket Policy           |
| -------------------- | -------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Recommended          | ❌ Legacy             | ✅ Yes                   |
| Level                | Per object or bucket | Entire bucket or prefix |
| Flexibility          | Limited              | Very flexible           |
| Conditions           | ❌ No                 | ✅ Yes                   |
| Cross-account access | ✅ Yes                | ✅ Yes                   |
| Force HTTPS          | ❌ No                 | ✅ Yes                   |
| Max size             | Small (20 KB)        | Larger / more powerful  |
| Default state        | ❌ Disabled           | ✅ Available             |


what is replication is s3?

Replication means S3 automatically copies objects from one bucket to another — either in the same region or different region.


Two Types of Replication

S3 Replication
    ├── CRR (Cross Region Replication)
    └── SRR (Same Region Replication)


How to Set Up Replication
Step 1 — Enable Versioning on Both Buckets

Source bucket → Properties → Bucket Versioning → Enable
Destination bucket → Properties → Bucket Versioning → Enable

Step 2 — Create Replication Rule

Source bucket → Management tab
Click Replication rules → Create replication rule

Step 3 — Configure the Rule

Rule name        → e.g. "replicate-to-india"
Status           → Enabled
Source scope     → Entire bucket OR specific prefix/tag
Destination      → Choose destination bucket
IAM Role         → Create new or use existing
